			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2022</a> paper:</span><br><i>Reflection as a Tool to Debug Objects</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/StevenCostiou.html">Steven Costiou</a>, <a href="../profile/VincentAranega.html">Vincent Aranega</a>, <a href="../profile/MarcusDenker.html">Marcus Denker</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3567512.3567517">10.1145/3567512.3567517</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The main artifact is a debugging approach/tooling pattern built using reflection.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> It exploits runtime reflection/introspection mechanisms to observe and control execution.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6a.html"><span class="tagL">T6A: Experience Reports</span></a><ul><li> It is grounded in practical experience building and using debuggers for objects.
</li></ul></li></ul>
